[src:uv-python/dependencies] To ensure that a dependency is only installed on a specific platform or on specific Python versions, use environment markers.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] See Python's environment marker documentation for a complete enumeration of the available markers and operators.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Dependency sources can also be changed per-platform.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] The `project.dependencies` table represents the dependencies that are used when uploading to PyPI or building a wheel.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Individual dependencies are specified using dependency specifiers syntax, and the table follows the PEP 621 standard.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] `project.dependencies` defines the list of packages that are required for the project, along with the version constraints that should be used when installing them.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Each entry includes a dependency name and version.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] An entry may include extras or environment markers for platform-specific packages.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] The `tool.uv.sources` table extends the standard dependency tables with alternative dependency sources, which are used during development.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Dependency sources add support for common patterns that are not supported by the `project.dependencies` standard, like editable installations and relative paths.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] If another tool is used, only the definitions in the standard project tables will be used.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] If another tool is being used for development, any metadata provided in the source table will need to be re-specified in the other tool's format.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] The above example will only work on x86-64 Linux, due to the specifics of the PyTorch index.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] See the PyTorch guide for more information about setting up PyTorch.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Using an `index` source *pins* a package to the given index — it will not be downloaded from other indexes.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] When defining an index, an `explicit` flag can be included to indicate that the index should *only* be used for packages that explicitly specify it in `tool.uv.sources`.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] If `explicit` is not set, other packages may be resolved from the index, if not found elsewhere.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] To add a Git dependency source, prefix a Git-compatible URL with `git+`.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Support for Git LFS is also configurable per source.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] By default, Git LFS objects will not be fetched.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Ensure Git LFS is installed and configured on your system before attempting to install sources using Git LFS, otherwise a build failure can occur.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] To add a URL source, provide a `https://` URL to either a wheel (ending in `.whl`) or a source distribution (typically ending in `.tar.gz` or `.zip`; see here for all supported formats).
[src:uv-python/dependencies] URL dependencies can also be manually added or edited in the `pyproject.toml` with the `{ url = <url> }` syntax.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] A `subdirectory` may be specified if the source distribution isn't in the archive root.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] To add a path source, provide the path of a wheel (ending in `.whl`), a source distribution (typically ending in `.tar.gz` or `.zip`; see here for all supported formats), or a directory containing a `pyproject.toml`.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] When using a directory as a path dependency, uv will attempt to build and install the target as a package by default.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] See the virtual dependency documentation for details.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] An editable installation is not used for path dependencies by default.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] For multiple packages in the same repository, *workspaces* may be a better fit.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] To declare a dependency on a workspace member, add the member name with `{ workspace = true }`.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] All workspace members must be explicitly stated.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] See the workspace documentation for more details on workspaces.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] You can limit a source to a given platform or Python version by providing dependency specifiers-compatible environment markers for the source.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] By specifying the marker on the source, uv will still include `httpx` on all platforms, but will download the source from GitHub on macOS, and fall back to PyPI on all other platforms.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] You can specify multiple sources for a single dependency by providing a list of sources, disambiguated by PEP 508-compatible environment markers.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] For example, to pull in different `httpx` tags on macOS vs.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] This strategy extends to using different indexes based on environment markers.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] The use of `--no-sources` will also prevent uv from discovering any workspace members that could satisfy a given dependency.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] It is common for projects that are published as libraries to make some features optional to reduce the default dependency tree.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] For example, Pandas has an `excel` extra and a `plot` extra to avoid installation of Excel parsers and `matplotlib` unless someone explicitly requires them.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Extras are requested with the `package[<extra>]` syntax, e.g., `pandas[plot, excel]`.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Optional dependencies are specified in `[project.optional-dependencies]`, a TOML table that maps from extra name to its dependencies, following dependency specifiers syntax.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Optional dependencies can have entries in `tool.uv.sources` the same as normal dependencies.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] If you have optional dependencies that conflict with one another, resolution will fail unless you explicitly declare them as conflicting.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Sources can also be declared as applying only to a specific optional dependency.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Unlike optional dependencies, development dependencies are local-only and will *not* be included in the project requirements when published to PyPI or other indexes.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] As such, development dependencies are not included in the `[project]` table.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Development dependencies can have entries in `tool.uv.sources` the same as normal dependencies.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] uv uses the `[dependency-groups]` table (as defined in PEP 735) for declaration of development dependencies.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] The `dev` group is special-cased; there are `--dev`, `--only-dev`, and `--no-dev` flags to toggle inclusion or exclusion of its dependencies.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] See `--no-default-groups` to disable all default groups instead.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Additionally, the `dev` group is synced by default.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Development dependencies can be divided into multiple groups, using the `--group` flag.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Once groups are defined, the `--all-groups`, `--no-default-groups`, `--group`, `--only-group`, and `--no-group` options can be used to include or exclude their dependencies.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] The `--dev`, `--only-dev`, and `--no-dev` flags are equivalent to `--group dev`, `--only-group dev`, and `--no-group dev` respectively.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] uv requires that all dependency groups are compatible with each other and resolves all groups together when creating the lockfile.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] If dependencies declared in one group are not compatible with those in another group, uv will fail to resolve the requirements of the project with an error.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] If you have dependency groups that conflict with one another, resolution will fail unless you explicitly declare them as conflicting.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] An included group's dependencies cannot conflict with the other dependencies declared in a group.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] By default, uv includes the `dev` dependency group in the environment (e.g., during `uv run` or `uv sync`).
[src:uv-python/dependencies] The default groups to include can be changed using the `tool.uv.default-groups` setting.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] To disable this behaviour during `uv run` or `uv sync`, use `--no-default-groups`.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] To exclude a specific default group, use `--no-group <name>`.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] By default, dependency groups must be compatible with your project's `requires-python` range.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Dependencies declared in this section will be combined with the contents in the `dependency-groups.dev`.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Eventually, the `dev-dependencies` field will be deprecated and removed.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] If a `tool.uv.dev-dependencies` field exists, `uv add --dev` will use the existing section instead of adding a new `dependency-groups.dev` section.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] If a project is structured as Python package, it may declare dependencies that are required to build the project, but not required to run it.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] These dependencies are specified in the `[build-system]` table under `build-system.requires`, following PEP 518.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] By default, uv will respect `tool.uv.sources` when resolving build dependencies.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] When publishing a package, we recommend running `uv build --no-sources` to ensure that the package builds correctly when `tool.uv.sources` is disabled, as is the case when using other build tools, like `pypa/build`.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] A regular installation of a directory with a Python package first builds a wheel and then installs that wheel into your virtual environment, copying all source files.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] When the package source files are edited, the virtual environment will contain outdated versions.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Editable installations solve this problem by adding a link to the project within the virtual environment (a `.pth` file), which instructs the interpreter to include the source files directly.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] There are some limitations to editables (mainly: the build backend needs to support them, and native modules aren't recompiled before import), but they are useful for development, as the virtual environment will always use the latest changes to the package.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] uv uses editable installation for workspace packages by default.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] uv allows dependencies to be "virtual", in which the dependency itself is not installed as a package, but its dependencies are.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] By default, dependencies are never virtual.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] A dependency with a `path` source can be virtual if it explicitly sets `tool.uv.package = false`.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Without this setting, uv treats the path dependency as a normal package and will attempt to build it, even if the project does not declare a build system.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Similarly, a dependency with a `workspace` source can be virtual if it explicitly sets `tool.uv.package = false`.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Without this setting, the workspace member will be built even if a build system is not declared.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Then the `child` workspace member would not be installed, but the transitive dependency `anyio` would be.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Then `child` would be built and installed.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] uv uses standard dependency specifiers, originally defined in PEP 508.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] The version specifiers are comma separated and added together, e.g., `foo >=1.2.3,<2,!=1.4.0` is interpreted as "a version of `foo` that's at least 1.2.3, but less than 2, and not 1.4.0".
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Specifiers are padded with trailing zeros if required, so `foo ==2` matches foo 2.0.0, too.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] A star can be used for the last digit with equals, e.g., `foo ==2.1.*` will accept any release from the 2.1 series.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Extras are comma-separated in square bracket between name and version, e.g., `pandas[excel,plot] ==2.2`.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Whitespace between extra names is ignored.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Some dependencies are only required in specific environments, e.g., a specific Python version or operating system.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] For example to install the `importlib-metadata` backport for the `importlib.metadata` module, use `importlib-metadata >=7.1.0,<8; python_version < '3.10'`.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] To install `colorama` on Windows (but omit it on other platforms), use `colorama >=0.4.6,<5; platform_system == "Windows"`.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Markers are combined with `and`, `or`, and parentheses, e.g., `aiohttp >=3.7.4,<4; (sys_platform != 'win32' or implementation_name != 'pypy') and python_version >= '3.10'`.
[src:uv-python/dependencies] Note that versions within markers must be quoted, while versions *outside* of markers must *not* be quoted.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] uv supports managing Python projects, which define their dependencies in a `pyproject.toml` file.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] The `main.py` file contains a simple "Hello world" program.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] A project consists of a few important parts that work together and allow uv to manage your project.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] In addition to the files created by `uv init`, uv will create a virtual environment and `uv.lock` file in the root of your project the first time you run a project command, i.e., `uv run`, `uv sync`, or `uv lock`.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] You'll use this file to specify dependencies, as well as details about the project such as its description or license.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] You can edit this file manually, or use commands like `uv add` and `uv remove` to manage your project from the terminal.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] See the official `pyproject.toml` guide for more details on getting started with the `pyproject.toml` format.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] You'll also use this file to specify uv configuration options in a `[tool.uv]` section.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] The `.python-version` file contains the project's default Python version.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] This file tells uv which Python version to use when creating the project's virtual environment.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] The `.venv` folder contains your project's virtual environment, a Python environment that is isolated from the rest of your system.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] This is where uv will install your project's dependencies.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] See the project environment documentation for more details.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] `uv.lock` is a cross-platform lockfile that contains exact information about your project's dependencies.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] Unlike the `pyproject.toml` which is used to specify the broad requirements of your project, the lockfile contains the exact resolved versions that are installed in the project environment.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] This file should be checked into version control, allowing for consistent and reproducible installations across machines.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] `uv.lock` is a human-readable TOML file but is managed by uv and should not be edited manually.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] See the lockfile documentation for more details.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] You can add dependencies to your `pyproject.toml` with the `uv add` command.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] The `--upgrade-package` flag will attempt to update the specified package to the latest compatible version, while keeping the rest of the lockfile intact.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] See the documentation on managing dependencies for more details.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] The `uv version` command can be used to read your package's version.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] See the publishing guide for details on updating your package version.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] `uv run` can be used to run arbitrary scripts or commands in your project environment.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] Prior to every `uv run` invocation, uv will verify that the lockfile is up-to-date with the `pyproject.toml`, and that the environment is up-to-date with the lockfile, keeping your project in-sync without the need for manual intervention.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] `uv run` guarantees that your command is run in an environment with all required dependencies at their locked versions.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] `uv run` does not remove extraneous packages (those not in the lockfile) from the environment by default.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] See handling of extraneous packages for details.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] The virtual environment must be active to run scripts and commands in the project without `uv run`.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] Virtual environment activation differs per shell and platform.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] See the documentation on running commands and scripts in projects for more details.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] `uv build` can be used to build source distributions and binary distributions (wheel) for your project.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] See the documentation on building projects for more details.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] To learn more about working on projects with uv, see the projects concept page and the command reference.
[src:uv-python/guides-projects] Or, read on to learn how to export a uv lockfile to different formats.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] A **package manager**, or **package management system**, is software that supports installing, upgrading, configuring, and removing software for the host system in a consistent manner.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] A package manager deals with *packages*, distributions of software and data in archive files.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Packages contain metadata, such as the software's name, description of its purpose, version number, vendor, checksum (usually a cryptographic hash function), and a list of dependencies necessary for the software to run properly.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Upon installation, metadata is stored in a local package database.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Package managers typically maintain a database of software dependencies and version information to prevent software mismatches and missing prerequisites.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] They work closely with software repositories, binary repository managers, and app stores.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Package managers are designed to eliminate the need for manual installs and updates.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] This can be particularly useful for large enterprises whose operating systems (OSes) typically consist of hundreds or even tens of thousands of distinct packages.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] An early package manager was SMIT (and its backend install) from IBM AIX.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] SMIT was introduced with AIX 3.0 in 1989.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Package managers like dpkg have existed as early as 1994.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Early package managers, from around 1994, had no automatic dependency resolution but could already simplify the process of adding and removing software from a running system.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] By around 1995, beginning with CPAN, package managers began handling package repository downloads, and dependency resolution and installation as needed, making it easier to install, uninstall and update software.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] A software package is an archive file containing a computer program as well as necessary metadata for its deployment.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] The program may be in source code that has to be compiled and built first.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Package metadata include the software's description, version number, and dependencies.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Package managers are charged with the task of finding, installing, maintaining or uninstalling packages upon the user's command.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Computer systems that rely on dynamic library linking, instead of static library linking, share executable libraries of machine instructions across packages and applications.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] In these systems, conflicting relationships between different packages requiring different versions of libraries results in a situation called *dependency hell*.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] On Microsoft Windows systems, this is also called *DLL hell* when working with dynamically-linked libraries.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Modern package managers have mostly solved these problems by allowing parallel installation of multiple library versions (e.g.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] OPENSTEP's *Framework* system), a dependency of any kind (e.g.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] *slots* in Gentoo Portage), and even packages compiled with different compiler versions (e.g. dynamic libraries built by the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, where a stable ABI does not exist), in order to enable other packages to specify which version they are linked or installed against.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] System administrators may install and maintain software using tools other than package managers.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] For example, a local administrator may download unpackaged source code, compile it, and install it.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] This may cause the local system to fall out of synchronization with the package manager's database.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] The local administrator will be required to take additional measures, such as manually managing some dependencies or integrating the changes into the package manager.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] There are tools to ensure that locally-compiled packages are integrated with the package management.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Upgrades of configuration files may be particularly troublesome.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Since package managers, at least on Unix systems, originated as extensions of file archivers, they can usually only overwrite or retain configuration files, rather than apply rules to them.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] There are exceptions to this that usually apply to kernel configuration (which, if broken, will render the computer unusable after a restart).
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Problems can be caused if the configuration file format changes; for instance, if the old file does not explicitly disable new options that should be disabled.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Some package managers, such as Debian's dpkg, allow configuration during installation.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] In other situations, packages are installed with the default configuration, which is then overwritten, for example in headless installations to a large number of computers.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] This kind of pre-configured installation is also supported by dpkg.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] To give users more control over the software they allow to be installed on their systems, and sometimes due to legal or convenience reasons on the distributors' side, packages are often downloaded from software repositories.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Many package managers can be configured to never upgrade certain packages, or to upgrade them only when critical vulnerabilities or instabilities are found in the previous version, as defined by the packager of the software.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] This process is called *upgrade suppression*, or *version pinning*.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Some of the more advanced package management features offer *cascading package removal*, in which all packages that depend on the target package and all packages that only it depends on are also removed.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Although commands are specific to each package manager, they are translatable to a large extent, as most package managers offer similar functions.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] The Arch Linux wiki offers an extensive overview of commands.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Linux distributions oriented to binary packages rely heavily on package management systems as their primary means of managing and maintaining software.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Mobile operating systems such as Android (Linux-based) and iOS (Unix-based) rely almost exclusively on their respective vendors' app stores and thus use their own dedicated package management systems.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] A package manager is often called an *install manager*, which can lead to a confusion between package managers and installers.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Most software configuration management systems treat building software and deploying software as separate, independent steps.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] A build automation utility typically takes human-readable source code files already on a computer, and automates the process of converting them into an executable package on the same or a remote computer.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Later, a package manager typically running on another computer downloads the pre-built executable and installs it.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] A few tools, such as Maak and A-A-P, are designed to handle both building and deployment, and can be used as either build automation utilities, package managers, or both.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] App stores can also be considered application-level package managers (without the ability to install all levels of programs).
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Unlike traditional package managers, app stores are designed to enable payment for the software itself (instead of for software development), and may only offer monolithic packages with no dependencies or dependency resolution.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] They are usually limited in their management functionality, due to focusing on ease-of-use over power or emergence, and are common in commercial operating systems and smart devices.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Package managers also often have only human-reviewed code.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Many app stores, such as Google Play and Apple's App Store, mainly screen apps using automated tools only; malware can pass these tests by detecting when the app is being tested, and delaying malicious activity.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] There are exceptions: the npm package database, for instance, relies entirely on post-publication review of its code, while the Debian package database has an extensive human review process before any package goes into the main database.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] The XZ Utils backdoor used years of trust-building to insert a backdoor, which was nonetheless caught while in the testing database.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Also known as binary repository manager, it is a software tool designed to optimize the download and storage of binary files, artifacts and packages used and produced in the software development process.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] These package managers aim to standardize the way enterprises treat all package types.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] They give users the ability to apply security and compliance metrics across all artifact types.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Universal package managers have been referred to as being at the center of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Each package manager relies on the format and metadata of the packages in its repository.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] That is, package managers need groups of files to be bundled along with appropriate metadata, such as dependencies.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Often, a core set of utilities manages the basic installation from these packages and multiple package managers use these utilities to provide additional functionality.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] For example, yum relies on rpm as a backend.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Yum extends the functionality of rpm by adding features such as simple configuration for maintaining a network of systems.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] As another example, the Synaptic Package Manager provides a graphical user interface by using the Advanced Packaging Tool (apt) library, which in turn relies on dpkg for core functionality.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Alien is a program that converts between different Linux package formats, supporting conversion between Linux Standard Base (LSB) compliant .rpm packages, .deb, Stampede (.slp), Solaris (.pkg) and Slackware (.tgz, .txz, .tbz, .tlz) packages.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] For mobile operating systems, Google Play uses the Android application package (APK) package format while Microsoft Store uses the APPX and XAP formats.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Both Google Play and Microsoft Store have eponymous package managers.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] By the nature of free and open-source software (FOSS), packages under similar and compatible licenses are available on a number of operating systems.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] These packages can be combined and distributed using configurable packaging systems to handle many permutations of software and manage version-specific dependencies and conflicts.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Some managers of FOSS packages are released as FOSS themselves.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] The ability to continuously upgrade third-party software is typically added by adding the URL of the corresponding repository to the package management's configuration file.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Besides system-level application managers, there are add-on package managers for operating systems with limited capabilities and for programming languages in which developers need the latest libraries.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Unlike system-level package managers, application-level package managers focus on a small part of the software system.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] They typically reside within a directory tree that is not maintained by the system-level manager, such as c:\cygwin or /opt/sw.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] This may not be the case for managers that deal with programming libraries, leading to possible conflicts, as both managers may claim to own a file and may break upgrades.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] Ian Murdock commented that package management is "the single biggest advancement Linux has brought to the industry", that it blurs the boundaries between operating systems and applications, and that it makes it "easier to push new innovations [...] into the marketplace and [...] evolve the OS".
[src:uv-python/package-manager] There is also a conference for package manager developers known as PackagingCon.
[src:uv-python/package-manager] It was established in 2021 with the aim to understand different approaches to package management.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Guido van Rossum began working on Python in the late 1980s as a successor to the ABC programming language.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python 3.0, released in 2008, was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Beginning with Python 3.5, capabilities and keywords for typing were added to the language, allowing optional static typing.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] As of 2026, the Python Software Foundation supports Python 3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13, and 3.14, following the project's annual release cycle and five-year support policy.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 is currently in the beta development phase, and the stable release is expected to launch in October 2026.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Earlier versions in the 3.x series have reached end-of-life and no longer receive security updates.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python has gained extensive use in the machine learning community.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] It is widely taught as an introductory programming language.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Since 2003, Python has consistently ranked among the top ten most popular programming languages in the TIOBE Programming Community Index, which ranks programming languages based on searches across 24 platforms.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python was conceived in the late 1980s by Guido van Rossum at Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica (CWI) in the Netherlands.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] It was designed as a successor to the ABC programming language, which was inspired by SETL, capable of exception handling and interfacing with the Amoeba operating system.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python implementation began in December 1989.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Van Rossum first released it in 1991 as Python 0.9.0.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] In January 2019, active Python core developers elected a five-member Steering Council to lead the project.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] The name *Python* derives from the British comedy series *Monty Python's Flying Circus*.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python 2.0 was released on 16 October 2000, featuring many new features such as list comprehensions, cycle-detecting garbage collection, reference counting, and Unicode support.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python 2.7's end-of-life was initially set for 2015, and then postponed to 2020 out of concern that a large body of existing code could not easily be forward-ported to Python 3.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] It no longer receives security patches or updates.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] While Python 2.7 and older versions are officially unsupported, a different unofficial Python implementation, PyPy, continues to support Python 2, i.e., "2.7.18+" (plus 3.11), with the plus signifying (at least some) "backported security updates".
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python 3.0 was released on 3 December 2008, and was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions, with some new semantics and changed syntax.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python 2.7.18, released in 2020, was the last release of Python 2.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Several releases in the Python 3.x series have added new syntax to the language, and made a few (considered very minor) backward-incompatible changes.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] As of May 2026, Python 3.14.6 is the latest stable release.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] All older 3.x versions had a security update down to Python 3.9.24 then again with 3.9.25, the final version in 3.9 series.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python 3.10 is, since November 2025, the oldest supported branch.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 has an alpha released, and Android has an official downloadable executable available for Python 3.14.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Releases receive two years of full support followed by three years of security support.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python is a multi-paradigm programming language.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Object-oriented programming and structured programming are fully supported, and many of their features support functional programming and aspect-oriented programming – including metaprogramming and metaobjects.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Many other paradigms are supported via extensions, including design by contract and logic programming.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python is often referred to as a *'glue language'* because it is purposely designed to be able to integrate components written in other languages.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python uses dynamic typing and a combination of reference counting and a cycle-detecting garbage collector for memory management.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] It uses dynamic name resolution (late binding), which binds method and variable names during program execution.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python's design offers some support for functional programming in the "Lisp tradition".
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] It has `filter`, `map`, and `reduce` functions; list comprehensions, dictionaries, sets, and generator expressions.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] The standard library has two modules (`itertools` and `functools`) that implement functional tools borrowed from Haskell and Standard ML.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] However, Python has received criticism for violating these principles and adding unnecessary language bloat.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Responses to these criticisms note that the Zen of Python is a guideline rather than a rule.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] The addition of some new features had been controversial: Guido van Rossum resigned as *Benevolent Dictator for Life* after conflict about adding the assignment expression operator in Python 3.8.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Nevertheless, rather than building all functionality into its core, Python was designed to be highly extensible through modules.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] This compact modularity has made it particularly popular as a means of adding programmable interfaces to existing applications.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Van Rossum's vision of a small core language with a large standard library and an easily extensible interpreter stemmed from his frustrations with ABC, which represented the opposite approach.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python claims to strive for a simpler, less-cluttered syntax and grammar, while giving developers a choice in their coding methodology.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python lacks `do .. while` loops, which Rossum considered harmful.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] In contrast to Perl's motto "there is more than one way to do it", Python advocates an approach where "there should be one – and preferably only one – obvious way to do it".
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] In practice, however, Python provides many ways to achieve a given goal.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] There are at least three ways to format a string literal, with no certainty as to which one a programmer should use.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python's developers typically prioritize readability over performance.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] For example, they reject patches to non-critical parts of the CPython reference implementation that would offer increases in speed that do not justify the cost of clarity and readability.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Execution speed can be improved by moving speed-critical functions to extension modules written in languages such as C, or by using a just-in-time compiler like PyPy.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Also, it is possible to transpile to other languages.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] However, this approach either fails to achieve the expected speed-up, since Python is a very dynamic language, or only a restricted subset of Python is compiled (with potential minor semantic changes).
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be a fun language to use.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] This goal is reflected in the name – a tribute to the British comedy group Monty Python – and in playful approaches to some tutorials and reference materials.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] For instance, some code examples use the terms "spam" and "eggs" (in reference to a Monty Python sketch), rather than the typical terms "foo" and "bar".
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] A common neologism in the Python community is *pythonic*, which has a broad range of meanings related to program style: Pythonic code may use Python idioms well; be natural or show fluency in the language; or conform with Python's minimalist philosophy and emphasis on readability.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] There are 3 kinds of PEPs, with those are being *standards track PEP*, *Informational PEP* and *Process PEP*s which has their own unique meanings.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] They were firstly introduced in 2000, inspired by other RfCs (requests for comments) and Desing Enhancement Proposals.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Most known PEPs are PEP – 1, PEP – 8, PEP – 20, PEP – 257 and others.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be an easily readable language.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Its formatting is visually uncluttered and often uses English keywords where other languages use punctuation.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Unlike many other languages, it does not use curly brackets to delimit blocks, and semicolons after statements are allowed but rarely used.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] It has fewer syntactic exceptions and special cases than C or Pascal.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python uses whitespace indentation, rather than curly brackets or keywords, to delimit blocks.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] An increase in indentation comes after certain statements; a decrease in indentation signifies the end of the current block.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Thus, the program's visual structure accurately represents its semantic structure.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] This feature is sometimes termed the off-side rule.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Some other languages use indentation this way; but in most, indentation has no semantic meaning.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] The recommended indent size is four spaces.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] The assignment statement (`=`) binds a name as a reference to a separate, dynamically allocated object.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Variables may subsequently be rebound at any time to any object.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] In Python, a variable name is a generic reference holder without a fixed data type; however, it always refers to *some* object with a type.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] This is called dynamic typing—in contrast to statically-typed languages, where each variable may contain only a value of a certain type.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python does not support tail call optimization or first-class continuations; according to Van Rossum, the language never will.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] However, better support for coroutine-like functionality is provided by extending Python's generators.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Before 2.5, generators were lazy iterators; data was passed unidirectionally out of the generator.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] From Python 2.5 on, it is possible to pass data back into a generator function; and from version 3.3, data can be passed through multiple stack levels.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] In Python, a distinction between expressions and statements is rigidly enforced, in contrast to languages such as Common Lisp, Scheme, or Ruby.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] A statement cannot be part of an expression; because of this restriction, expressions such as list and `dict` comprehensions (and lambda expressions) cannot contain statements.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] As a particular case, an assignment statement such as `a = 1` cannot be part of the conditional expression of a conditional statement.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python uses duck typing, and it has typed objects but untyped variable names.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Type constraints are not checked at definition time; rather, operations on an object may fail at usage time, indicating that the object is not of an appropriate type.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Despite being dynamically typed, Python is strongly typed, forbidding operations that are poorly defined (e.g., adding a number and a string) rather than quietly attempting to interpret them.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python allows programmers to define their own types using classes, most often for object-oriented programming.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] New instances of classes are constructed by calling the class, for example, `SpamClass()` or `EggsClass()`); the classes are instances of the metaclass `type` (which is an instance of itself), thereby allowing metaprogramming and reflection.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Before version 3.0, Python had two kinds of classes, both using the same syntax: *old-style* and *new-style*.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Current Python versions support the semantics of only the new style.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python supports optional type annotations.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] These annotations are not enforced by the language, but may be used by external tools such as **mypy** to catch errors.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python includes a module `typing` including several type names for type annotations.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Also, mypy supports a Python compiler called mypyc, which leverages type annotations for optimization.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python includes conventional symbols for arithmetic operators (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`), the floor-division operator `//`, and the modulo operator `%`.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] (With the modulo operator, a remainder can be negative, e.g., `4 % -3 == -2`.) Python also offers the `**` symbol for exponentiation, e.g.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] These operators work as in traditional mathematics; with the same precedence rules, the infix operators `+` and `-` can also be unary, to represent positive and negative numbers respectively.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Division between integers produces floating-point results.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] In Python terms, the `/` operator represents *true division* (or simply *division*), while the `//` operator represents *floor division.* Before version 3.0, the `/` operator represents *classic division*.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Rounding towards negative infinity, though a different method than in most languages, adds consistency to Python.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] For instance, this rounding implies that the equation `(a + b)//b == a//b + 1` is always true.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Also, the rounding implies that the equation `b*(a//b) + a%b == a` is valid for both positive and negative values of `a`.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] As expected, the result of `a%b` lies in the half-open interval [0, *b*), where `b` is a positive integer; however, maintaining the validity of the equation requires that the result must lie in the interval (*b*, 0] when `b` is negative.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python provides a `round` function for rounding a float to the nearest integer.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] For tie-breaking, Python 3 uses the *round to even* method: `round(1.5)` and `round(2.5)` both produce `2`.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python allows Boolean expressions that contain multiple equality relations to be consistent with general usage in mathematics.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] For example, the expression `a < b < c` tests whether `a` is less than `b` and `b` is less than `c`.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] C-derived languages interpret this expression differently: in C, the expression would first evaluate `a < b`, resulting in 0 or 1, and that result would then be compared with `c`.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python uses arbitrary-precision arithmetic for all integer operations.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] The `Decimal` type/class in the `decimal` module provides decimal floating-point numbers to a pre-defined arbitrary precision with several rounding modes.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] The `Fraction` class in the `fractions` module provides arbitrary precision for rational numbers.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Due to Python's extensive mathematics library and the third-party library NumPy, the language is frequently used for scientific scripting in tasks such as numerical data processing and manipulation.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Functions are created in Python by using the `def` keyword.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] A function is defined similarly to how it is called, by first providing the function name and then the required parameters.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] To assign a default value to a function parameter in case no actual value is provided at run time, variable-definition syntax can be used inside the function header.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python's large standard library is commonly cited as one of its greatest strengths.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] For Internet-facing applications, many standard formats and protocols such as MIME and HTTP are supported.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] The language includes modules for creating graphical user interfaces, connecting to relational databases, generating pseudorandom numbers, arithmetic with arbitrary-precision decimals, manipulating regular expressions, and unit testing.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Some parts of the standard library are covered by specifications—for example, the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI) implementation `wsgiref` follows PEP 333—but most parts are specified by their code, internal documentation, and test suites.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] However, because most of the standard library is cross-platform Python code, only a few modules must be altered or rewritten for variant implementations.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] As of 13 March 2025, the Python Package Index (PyPI), the official repository for third-party Python software, contains over 614,339 packages.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Most Python implementations (including CPython) include a read–eval–print loop (REPL); this permits the environment to function as a command line interpreter, with which users enter statements sequentially and receive results immediately.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Also, CPython is bundled with an integrated development environment (IDE) called IDLE, which is oriented toward beginners.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Other shells, including IDLE and IPython, add additional capabilities such as improved auto-completion, session-state retention, and syntax highlighting.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] CPython is the reference implementation of Python.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] This implementation is written in C, meeting the C11 standard since version 3.11.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Older versions use the C89 standard with several select C99 features, but third-party extensions are not limited to older C versions—e.g., they can be implemented using C11 or C++.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] CPython compiles Python programs into an intermediate bytecode, which is then executed by a virtual machine.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] CPython is distributed with a large standard library written in a combination of C and native Python.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] CPython is available for many platforms, including Windows and most modern Unix-like systems, including macOS (and Apple M1 Macs, since Python 3.9.1, using an experimental installer).
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Starting with Python 3.9, the Python installer intentionally fails to install on Windows 7 and 8; Windows XP was supported until Python 3.5.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Old Python versions unofficially support VMS (mostly supporting) and OpenVMS x86-64 has Python 3.10 support.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Platform portability was one of Python's earliest priorities.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] During development of Python 1 and 2, even OS/2 and Solaris were supported; since that time, support has been dropped for many platforms.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] All current Python versions (since 3.7) support only operating systems that feature multithreading, by now supporting not nearly as many operating systems (dropping many outdated) than in the past.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] All alternative implementations have at least slightly different semantics.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] For example, an alternative may include unordered dictionaries, in contrast to other current Python versions.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] As another example in the larger Python ecosystem, PyPy does not support the full C Python API.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Creating an executable with Python often is done by bundling an entire Python interpreter into the executable, which causes binary sizes to be massive for small programs, yet there exist implementations that are capable of truly compiling Python.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Stackless Python is a significant fork of CPython that implements microthreads.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] This implementation uses the call stack differently, thus allowing massively concurrent programs.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] A performance comparison among various Python implementations, using a non-numerical (combinatorial) workload, was presented at EuroSciPy '13.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] In addition, Python's performance relative to other programming languages is benchmarked by The Computer Language Benchmarks Game.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] There are several approaches to optimizing Python performance, despite the inherent slowness of an interpreted language.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python's development is conducted mostly through the *Python Enhancement Proposal* (PEP) process; this process is the primary mechanism for proposing major new features, collecting community input on issues, and documenting Python design decisions.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python coding style is covered in PEP 8.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Outstanding PEPs are reviewed and commented on by the Python community and the steering council.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Enhancement of the language corresponds with development of the CPython reference implementation.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] The mailing list python-dev is the primary forum for the language's development.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Specific issues were originally discussed in the Roundup bug tracker hosted by the foundation.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] In 2022, all issues and discussions were migrated to GitHub.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Development originally took place on a self-hosted source-code repository running Mercurial, until Python moved to GitHub in January 2017.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Many alpha, beta, and release-candidates are also released as previews and for testing before final releases.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Although there is a rough schedule for releases, they are often delayed if the code is not ready yet.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python's development team monitors the state of the code by running a large unit test suite during development.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] The major academic conference on Python is PyCon.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Also, there are special Python mentoring programs, such as PyLadies.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python's name is inspired by the British comedy group Monty Python, whom Python creator Guido van Rossum enjoyed while developing the language.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Monty Python references appear frequently in Python code and culture; for example, the metasyntactic variables often used in Python literature are *spam* and *eggs*, rather than the traditional *foo* and *bar*.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Also, the official Python documentation contains various references to Monty Python routines.
[src:uv-python/python-programming-language] Python users are sometimes referred to as "Pythonistas".
[src:uv-python/software-repository] A **software repository**, or **repo** for short, is a storage location for software packages.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Often a table of contents is also stored, along with metadata.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] A software repository is typically managed by source or version control, or repository managers.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Package managers allow automatically installing and updating repositories, sometimes called "packages".
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Many software publishers and other organizations maintain servers on the Internet for this purpose, either free of charge or for a subscription fee.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Repositories may be solely for particular programs, such as CPAN for the Perl programming language, or for an entire operating system.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Operators of such repositories typically provide a package management system, tools intended to search for, install and otherwise manipulate software packages from the repositories.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] For example, many Linux distributions use Advanced Packaging Tool (APT), commonly found in Debian based distributions, or Yellowdog Updater, Modified (yum) found in Red Hat based distributions.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] There are also multiple independent package management systems, such as pacman, used in Arch Linux and equo, found in Sabayon Linux.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] As software repositories are designed to include useful packages, major repositories are designed to be malware free.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] If a computer is configured to use a digitally signed repository from a reputable vendor, and is coupled with an appropriate permissions system, this significantly reduces the threat of malware to these systems.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] As a side effect, many systems that have these abilities do not need anti-malware software such as antivirus software.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Most major Linux distributions have many repositories around the world that mirror the main repository.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] At client side, a package manager helps installing from and updating the repositories.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] A package management system is different from a package development process.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] A typical use of a package management system is to facilitate the integration of code from possibly different sources into a coherent stand-alone operating unit.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Thus, a package management system might be used to produce a distribution of Linux, possibly a distribution tailored to a specific restricted application.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] A package development process, by contrast, is used to manage the co-development of code and documentation of a collection of functions or routines with a common theme, producing thereby a package of software functions that typically will not be complete and usable by themselves.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] A good package development process will help users conform to good documentation and coding practices, integrating some level of unit testing.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] The following table lists a few languages with repositories for contributed software.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] The "Autochecks" column describes the routine checks done.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Very few people have the ability to test their software under multiple operating systems with different versions of the core code and with other contributed packages they may use.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] For the R programming language, the Comprehensive R Archive Network (CRAN) runs tests routinely.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] To understand how this is valuable, imagine a situation with two developers, Sally and John.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Sally only runs the current version of the software under one version of Microsoft Windows, and has only tested it in that environment.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] At more or less regular intervals, CRAN tests Sally's contribution under a dozen combinations of operating systems and versions of the core R language software.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] If one of them generates an error, she gets that error message.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] With luck, that error message details may provide enough input to allow enable a fix for the error, even if she cannot replicate it with her current hardware and software.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Next, suppose John contributes to the repository a package B that uses a package A.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Package B passes all the tests and is made available to users.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Later, Sally submits an improved version of A, which breaks B.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] The autochecks make it possible to provide information to John so he can fix the problem.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] This example exposes both a strength and a weakness in the R contributed-package system: CRAN supports this kind of automated testing of contributed packages, but packages contributed to CRAN need not specify the versions of other contributed packages that they use.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Procedures for requesting specific versions of packages exist, but contributors might not use those procedures.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Beyond this, a repository such as CRAN running regular checks of contributed packages actually provides an extensive if *ad hoc* test suite for development versions of the core language.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] If Sally (in the example above) gets an error message she does not understand or thinks is inappropriate, especially from a development version of the language, she can (and often does with R) ask the core development-team for the language for help.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] In this way, the repository can contribute to improving the quality of the core language software.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Package managers help manage repositories and the distribution of them.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] If a repository is updated, a package manager will usually allow a user to update that repository through the manager.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] It also helps to manage things such as dependencies between other repositories.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] In an enterprise environment, a software repository is usually used to store artifacts, or to mirror external repositories which may be inaccessible due to security restrictions.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] One example is Sonatype Nexus Repository.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] At server side, a software repository is typically managed by source control or repository managers.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Some of the repository managers allow to aggregate other repository location into one URL and provide a caching proxy.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] When doing continuous builds many artifacts are produced and often centrally stored, so automatically deleting the ones which are not released is important.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] As part of the development lifecycle, source code is continuously being built into binary artifacts using continuous integration.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] This may interact with a binary repository manager much like a developer would by getting artifacts from the repositories and pushing builds there.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Artifacts and packages inherently mean different things.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Artifacts are simply an output or collection of files (ex.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] JAR, WAR, DLLS, RPM etc.) and one of those files may contain metadata (e.g.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Whereas packages are a single archive file in a well-defined format (ex.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] NuGet) that contain files appropriate for the package type (ex.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Many artifacts result from builds but other types are crucial as well.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Packages are essentially one of two things: a library or an application.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Compared to source files, binary artifacts are often larger by orders of magnitude, they are rarely deleted or overwritten (except for rare cases such as snapshots or nightly builds), and they are usually accompanied by much metadata such as id, package name, version, license and more.
[src:uv-python/software-repository] Metadata describes a binary artifact, is stored and specified separately from the artifact itself, and can have several additional uses.
[src:uv-python/uv-pip] uv provides a drop-in replacement for common `pip`, `pip-tools`, and `virtualenv` commands.
[src:uv-python/uv-pip] These commands work directly with the virtual environment, in contrast to uv's primary interfaces where the virtual environment is managed automatically.
[src:uv-python/uv-pip] The `uv pip` interface exposes the speed and functionality of uv to power users and projects that are not ready to transition away from `pip` and `pip-tools`.
[src:uv-python/uv-pip] Please note these commands do not *exactly* implement the interfaces and behavior of the tools they are based on.
[src:uv-python/uv-pip] The further you stray from common workflows, the more likely you are to encounter differences.
[src:uv-python/uv-pip] Consult the pip-compatibility guide for details.
[src:uv-python/uv-pip] The pip interface is named as such to highlight its dedicated purpose of providing low-level commands that match pip's interface and to separate it from the rest of uv's commands which operate at a higher level of abstraction.
[src:uv-python/uv] An extremely fast Python package and project manager, written in Rust.
[src:uv-python/uv] uv is backed by Astral, the creators of Ruff.
